{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":"2026-04-17T01:54:23.592Z","tool_name":"write_file","tool_id":"write_file_1776390863590_0","parameters":{"content":"# Verification Report — T-018@20260416t181925zc-verify.md\n\n**Verify Agent:** Gemini CLI\n**Date:** Thursday, April 16, 2026\n**Artifacts Reviewed:**\n- `my-claw/tools/senseweave/render/export.py`\n- `my-claw/tools/senseweave/render/audio_sidecar.py`\n- `my-claw/tools/senseweave/ixml_chunk_writer.py`\n- `my-claw/tools/daemon.py`\n- `tests/test_render_export.py`\n- `tests/test_render_audio_sidecar.py`\n- `tests/test_ixml_chunk_writer.py`\n- `tests/test_first_boot.py`\n- `tests/test_governor_integration.py`\n\n## Correctness\nThe implementation correctly integrates provenance capture into the audio export pipeline. The `export_audio` function collects rule-stack context (applied rules, quantities, and metadata) and passes it to both the iXML chunk writer (embedded in WAV) and the JSON sidecar writer. Verification tests confirm that the provenance is accurately preserved and restorable from both formats.\n\n## Completeness\nThe solution covers all requested aspects:\n- Provenance collection from `PerformedPart` or explicit parameters.\n- Embedding of `rule_stack` and `rule_quantities` as iXML metadata in WAV files.\n- Generation of `.meta.json` sidecars containing full provenance, events (with inherited rule-stacks), performance intents, and section envelopes.\n- Handling of edge cases like empty rule stacks and WAV readability after modification.\n\n## Consistency\nThe code follows the established patterns in the `senseweave/render` package. The use of frozen dataclasses for `ExportResult` and the naming conventions for sidecar files are consistent with the rest of the project. The integration into the `poll_loop` startup sequence in `daemon.py` also aligns with recent hardening requirements.\n\n## Security\nNo security vulnerabilities were identified. Metadata serialization uses standard JSON and XML libraries. File operations use safe patterns (temporary files with `os.replace` for sidecars). The hardening of the `bootstrap_identity` sequence ensures that the instance identity is minted and persisted before any external announcement occurs, preventing unauthenticated or anonymous federation broadcasts.\n\n## Quality\nThe code is high quality, well-documented, and backed by a comprehensive test suite. Ruff checks passed cleanly. Mypy reported no errors in the core provenance files (though unrelated errors persist in the broader codebase). The tests are surgical and cover both successful round-trips and error conditions.\n\n## Issues Found\n- [x] Hardening gap in `daemon.py` — severity: minor (fixed). `bootstrap_identity()` was called after the `startup_banner` in `daemon.py`, unlike in `cypherclaw_daemon.py`. This was corrected by moving the identity bootstrap to the earliest possible point in the startup flow.\n- [x] `pip install -e '.[dev]'` failure — severity: minor (environment/sandbox). The command failed with `Operation not permitted` due to macOS Seatbelt restrictions on the `~/.local/lib` directory. However, the existing environment was already sufficient to run the full test suite successfully.\n\n## Verdict: PASS\n\n## Notes for Lead Agent\nThe core provenance integration is solid and correctly implements the spec. The minor startup ordering inconsistency in `daemon.py` has been addressed to satisfy the mandatory hardening checks. The project is now ready for the next phase of deployment.\n","file_path":"sdp/verification/t-018@20260416t181925zc-verify.md"}}
